, 			{
				"box" : 				{
					"id" : "obj-19",
					"linecount" : 4,
					"maxclass" : "comment",
					"numinlets" : 1,
					"numoutlets" : 0,
					"patching_rect" : [ 344.473685145378113, 174.0, 250.0, 60.0 ],
					"text" : "The faders allow you get a feel how a sigmoid or logit mapping would work on an input parameter. Set a steepness and a shift and see how the faders behave."
				}

			}
, 			{
				"box" : 				{
					"id" : "obj-17",
					"linecount" : 5,
					"maxclass" : "comment",
					"numinlets" : 1,
					"numoutlets" : 0,
					"patching_rect" : [ 11.0, 63.0, 677.947370290756226, 74.0 ],
					"text" : "This patch demonstrates the sigmoid-logit abstractions in three flavours: trigonometric, algebraic and logistic. Sigmoid-logit mappings map a linear input to an S-shaped curve giving preference to either the extremes (sigmoid) or center (logit) values, depending on the steepness. The abstractions are programmed to form a sigmoid curve when the steepness parameter is greater than 0 and a logit curve when it is smaller than 0.The second parameter, called shift, can be used to shift the S curve either along the x-axis (in the sigmoid case) or y-axis (in the logit case). This adds more flexibility to the mapping."
				}

			}
